    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-12-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-12-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="497"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d497">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/586.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Mexican Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy of Mexico</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-12-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 23, 1910</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 494.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor to inform your excellency
                    that I have just received a telegram from the department of foreign relations
                        <pb facs="0461" n="379" xml:id="pg_379"/> of my country informing me that
                    armed insurgents are now crossing from El Paso to Ciudad Juárez in spite of the
                    prohibitive order issued on the subject by this Government.</p>
                <p>As this implies violation of the neutrality laws by individuals who cross the
                    boundary line in arms with the deliberate intention to foment revolt in a
                    friendly country, I ask that your excellency be pleased to renew by wire the
                    necessary orders to the local authorities having knowledge of the matter, so as
                    to prevent the commission of the acts above referred to.</p>
                <p>Thanking [etc.],</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">F. L. de la Barra</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
